04-24 19:37:22.837 I/NARR-STATE(27696): narrationState → Speaking(segment=NarrationSegment(id=poi_narration_1618182376491372, text=You're looking at one of the oldest houses in the United States still standing in its original form. The John Ward House, built between 1684 and 1723, is a perfect example of what we call First Period architecture – the building style brought over by the earliest English settlers. Imagine Salem in the early 18th century: a bustling port, but still a small town where everyone knew everyone else. John Ward was a prosperous merchant, and this house reflected his status. Notice the simple, asymmetrical lines, the steep roof, the small windows. It’s a far cry from the grand mansions that would come later. In the early 20th century, antiquarian George Francis Dow meticulously restored the house, preserving its original character. Today, the Peabody Essex Museum owns and operates it as a museum, offering a glimpse into the lives of those who first settled this land. The house was designated a National Historic Landmark in 1968, recognizing its importance to our nation’s story. Stand here a moment and picture the smoke curling from the chimney, the scent of woodsmoke and sea salt in the air, and the voices of a family building a life in a new world., type=LONG_NARRATION, poiName=John Ward House, voiceId=en-us-x-tpd-local, kind=POI, category=null, refId=poi_narration, isReplay=false)) (autoPlay=true, queueSize=0)
